snippet.textDisplay:
THIS IS NOT A BENGALI SONG; it is a language called Kamatapuri which is distinctly different from Bengali.
It was the state language spoken in the Kamata kingdom in ancient India, ruled by the Koches.

The lady who sang this song is Pratima Baruah, a Koch woman from the royal family of Gauripur in western Assam's Dhubri district.

Kamatapuri language is still spoken by many communities, including the Koch Rajbangshi community, residing in Rangpur Division in Bangladesh, northern West Bengal, and western Goalpara of Assam in India.

It is utterly sad and shameful that none of the creators credit her in any way while remaking this song. This comment is not for the makers who chose to intentionally disregard the singer and the treasure of the community, but for the music connoisseurs who are keen to not only enjoy music but also be aware of its origin and history. The song is for Pratima Baruah and the Koch Rajbangshi community, who hold this popular folk song close to their hearts.
